btl_state
BTR_STATE_01_01	Harsh Sunlight
BTR_STATE_01_02	The harsh sunlight weather condition.\nIt boosts the power of Fire-type moves and\nlowers the power of Water-type moves.
BTR_STATE_02_01	Rain
BTR_STATE_02_02	The rain weather condition.\nIt boosts the power of Water-type moves and\nlowers the power of Fire-type moves.
BTR_STATE_03_01	Sandstorm
BTR_STATE_03_02	The sandstorm weather condition.\nAt the end of each turn, it damages all Pokémon\nthat are not Rock, Ground, or Steel types.\nIt boosts the Sp. Def of Rock-type Pokémon.
BTR_STATE_04_01	Hail
BTR_STATE_04_02	The hail weather condition.\nAt the end of each turn, it damages all Pokémon\nthat are not Ice types.
BTR_STATE_08_01	Trick Room
BTR_STATE_08_02	Slower Pokémon get to move first for five turns.
BTR_STATE_11_01	Critical Hit Boost
BTR_STATE_11_02	The Pokémon is more likely to land critical hits.
BTR_STATE_12_01	Confusion
BTR_STATE_12_02	The Pokémon may hurt itself in its confusion.\nThe effect lasts for one to four turns.
BTR_STATE_13_01	Infatuation
BTR_STATE_13_02	The Pokémon is less likely to unleash an attack\non Pokémon of the opposite gender.
BTR_STATE_05_01	Electric Terrain
BTR_STATE_05_02	For five turns, Pokémon on the ground won’t\nfall asleep.\nThe power of Electric-type moves is boosted.
BTR_STATE_16_01	Encore
BTR_STATE_16_02	Due to Encore, the Pokémon can use only\n[VAR 0107(0000)] for three turns.
BTR_STATE_17_01	No Ability
BTR_STATE_17_02	The Pokémon’s Ability loses its effect.
BTR_STATE_18_01	Torment
BTR_STATE_18_02	The Pokémon can’t use the same move twice\nin a row.
BTR_STATE_19_01	Tailwind
BTR_STATE_19_02	The Speed stats of a Pokémon and its allies are\ndoubled for four turns.
BTR_STATE_21_01	Grudge
BTR_STATE_21_02	If the Pokémon faints by an opponent’s move,\nthe PP of that move will be reduced to 0.
BTR_STATE_06_01	Grassy Terrain
BTR_STATE_06_02	For five turns, Pokémon on the ground will have\na little HP restored at the end of each turn.\nThe power of Grass-type moves is boosted.
BTR_STATE_07_01	Misty Terrain
BTR_STATE_07_02	For five turns, Pokémon on the ground won’t get\nany status conditions.\nDamage from Dragon-type moves is halved.
BTR_STATE_24_01	Move Disabled
BTR_STATE_24_02	For four turns, the Pokémon will be unable to\nuse [VAR 0107(0000)].
BTR_STATE_25_01	Can’t Escape
BTR_STATE_25_02	The Pokémon can’t flee or be switched out.
BTR_STATE_26_01	Lock-On
BTR_STATE_26_02	The next move used by the Pokémon will be sure\nto hit the target that was locked on to.
BTR_STATE_09_01	Magic Room
BTR_STATE_09_02	Pokémon can’t use their held items for five turns.
BTR_STATE_28_01	Charge
BTR_STATE_28_02	The power of an Electric-type move will be\ndoubled if used in the turn after charging.
BTR_STATE_29_01	Gravity
BTR_STATE_29_02	Moves are more likely to hit for five turns.\nGround-type moves will hit Flying-type\nPokémon and Pokémon with the Levitate Ability.\nMoves that require action midair can’t be used.
BTR_STATE_30_01	Mist
BTR_STATE_30_02	The Pokémon’s stats won’t be lowered for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_31_01	Safeguard
BTR_STATE_31_02	The Pokémon is protected from status conditions\nfor five turns.
BTR_STATE_32_01	Stealth Rock
BTR_STATE_32_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will\ntake damage.
BTR_STATE_33_01	Stockpile
BTR_STATE_33_02	The Pokémon’s Defense and Sp. Def stats\ngo up while stockpiling.
BTR_STATE_34_01	Taunt
BTR_STATE_34_02	The Pokémon can only use moves that\ndeal damage.
BTR_STATE_36_01	Magnet Rise
BTR_STATE_36_02	Ground-type moves won’t hit the Pokémon\nfor five turns.
BTR_STATE_37_01	Toxic Spikes
BTR_STATE_37_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will\nbe poisoned.\nFlying-type Pokémon or Pokémon with\nthe Levitate Ability will not be affected.
BTR_STATE_10_01	Wonder Room
BTR_STATE_10_02	Pokémon’s Defense and Sp. Def are swapped for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_39_01	Wish
BTR_STATE_39_02	The Pokémon in this spot will have its HP restored\non the turn after Wish was used.
BTR_STATE_41_01	Ingrain
BTR_STATE_41_02	The Pokémon regains some HP at the end of\neach turn.\nIngrained Pokémon can’t be switched out.
BTR_STATE_42_01	Curse
BTR_STATE_42_02	The Pokémon takes damage at the end\nof each turn.
BTR_STATE_15_01	Drowsy
BTR_STATE_15_02	The Pokémon will fall asleep at the end of the\nturn if it remains on the battlefield.
BTR_STATE_44_01	Light Screen
BTR_STATE_44_02	Damage from special moves is halved for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_45_01	Reflect
BTR_STATE_45_02	Damage from physical moves is halved for\nfive turns.
BTR_STATE_46_01	Imprison
BTR_STATE_46_02	If a Pokémon affected by Imprison knows any\nmoves also known by the user of Imprison, it is\nprevented from using those moves.
BTR_STATE_47_01	Counting Down
BTR_STATE_47_02	All Pokémon in this battle state will faint after\nthree turns.
BTR_STATE_48_01	Spikes
BTR_STATE_48_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will\ntake damage.\nFlying-type Pokémon or Pokémon with\nthe Levitate Ability will not be affected.
BTR_STATE_50_01	Destiny Bond
BTR_STATE_50_02	If the Pokémon is knocked out by an opponent,\nthat opponent will also faint.
BTR_STATE_40_01	Sticky Web
BTR_STATE_40_02	Pokémon that switch into battle will have their\nSpeed lowered.
BTR_STATE_52_01	Leech Seed
BTR_STATE_52_02	Leech Seed steals some of the Pokémon’s HP\nat the end of each turn and gives it to\nthe opponent.
BTR_STATE_53_01	Lock-On
BTR_STATE_53_02	Any move used against a locked-on target will\nbe sure to hit.
BTR_STATE_54_01	Bound
BTR_STATE_54_02	The Pokémon is bound and takes damage\nevery turn.
BTR_STATE_56_01	Outrage
BTR_STATE_56_02	The Pokémon rampages and attacks for two to\nthree turns. It then becomes confused.
BTR_STATE_57_01	Rampaging
BTR_STATE_57_02	The Pokémon rampages and attacks for two to\nthree turns. It then becomes confused.
BTR_STATE_58_01	Petal Dance
BTR_STATE_58_02	The Pokémon rampages and attacks for two to\nthree turns. It then becomes confused.
BTR_STATE_59_01	Badly Poisoned
BTR_STATE_59_02	The Pokémon is badly poisoned. The damage\nthe Pokémon takes from the poison worsens\nevery turn.
BTR_STATE_61_01	Uproar
BTR_STATE_61_02	The Pokémon attacks and causes an uproar for\nthree turns. During this time, no Pokémon can\nfall asleep.
BTR_STATE_62_01	Aqua Ring
BTR_STATE_62_02	The Pokémon is enveloped in a veil made of\nwater. It regains some HP every turn.
BTR_STATE_64_01	Smack Down
BTR_STATE_64_02	The Pokémon has been knocked out of the sky\nand has fallen to the ground.
BTR_STATE_63_01	Autotomize
BTR_STATE_63_02	The Pokémon’s weight is reduced, and its Speed\nis sharply increased.
BTR_STATE_73_01	Throat Chop
BTR_STATE_73_02	The Pokémon can’t use any sound-based moves\nfor two turns.
BTR_STATE_75_01	Laser Focus
BTR_STATE_75_02	The next move used will always result in\na critical hit.
BTR_STATE_74_01	Aurora Veil
BTR_STATE_74_02	For five turns, the power of special and physical\nmoves will be halved.

tips
SS_tips_002	 Close
SS_tips_003	 Next
SS_tips_004	[VAR 0201(0000)]/[VAR 0201(0001)]
SS_tips_005	Adventure Guide
SS_tips_007	Open the X menu by pressing the [VAR FF00(0006)]X Button[VAR FF00(0000)]!\nYou can save your progress by selecting [VAR FF00(0006)]Save[VAR FF00(0000)]\nfrom the X menu!\nYou can also check your location and your next\ndestination by selecting the [VAR FF00(0006)]Town Map[VAR FF00(0000)].\nAnd you can check this Adventure Guide anytime you\nwant in the Key Items section of your Bag.
SS_tips_009	Y-Comm
SS_tips_010	Y-Comm offers many ways to connect with other\nplayers! You’ll be welcome to swap Pokémon, take\npart in Pokémon battles, and more!\nThere’s never a shortage of things to do!
SS_tips_012	Normally, you can use Y-Comm to connect with\npeople close-by. But if you press the + Button and\nconnect to the internet, you’ll be able to connect with\npeople around the world!
SS_tips_013	When stamps arrive in Y-Comm while you’re out\non your adventure, it means that other Trainers are\naround and looking for someone to connect with.\nPress the Y Button to see who’s around!
SS_tips_014	Select a stamp that shows the silhouette of a Pokémon\non it, and you’ll be able to team up with your fellow\nTrainers to battle Pokémon!
SS_tips_015	Pokémon League Cards
SS_tips_016	Show off your achievements by making a League Card!\nYou can customize your card using the Card Maker\nfound at every Pokémon Center. Doing so will also\nupdate your card with all your latest information!
SS_tips_017	Trainers all have their own League Cards, and you can\nswap cards with other Trainers that you connect with\nusing communication features. You can view all the\nLeague Cards you’ve collected by checking out your\nalbum, which you can find in the League Card option\nof the X menu.
SS_tips_019	The Battle Stadium
SS_tips_020	In the Battle Stadium, you can connect to other\nTrainers around the world to take part in Link Battles\nand various battle competitions against one another.
SS_tips_021	Casual Battles let you easily connect with all kinds\nof other players for battles—and for a bit of fun!\nYou might see some unexpected Pokémon and moves\nbeing used in these easygoing battles.
SS_tips_022	Ranked Battles are the real deal. This is where\nserious Trainers go to take one another on and try\nto reach the highest ranks. Your rank shows how strong\nyour team is, and it can go up and down based on\nthe results of your battles.
SS_tips_023	Online Competitions use a different system to measure\nyour skill as a Trainer. Here you earn a number rating\nthat shows where you stand among the competition.\nFor a fixed period of time, you’ll battle numerous other\nTrainers, and those battles will make your rating go up\nor down. Unlike other battle modes, it’s up to you to\nsearch out and select a competition you’ll choose to\ntake part in.
SS_tips_024	The Dynamax Phenomenon
SS_tips_025	In the Galar region, Pokémon can become far larger\nthan usual in certain places. This transformation is\ncalled “Dynamaxing.” Press the [VAR FF00(0006)]Dynamax button\n[VAR FF00(0000)]when your Dynamax Band lights up to Dynamax\nyour Pokémon.
SS_tips_026	Your Pokémon can only Dynamax for [VAR FF00(0006)]three turns[VAR FF00(0000)]!\nDuring that time, your Dynamax Pokémon can use\nextremely powerful moves known as [VAR FF00(0006)]Max Moves[VAR FF00(0000)].\nThese Max Moves not only deal tremendous damage—\nthey can also trigger special effects! The exact effect\nchanges depending on the type of the move used.\nChoose carefully when to Dynamax your Pokémon, and\nsmash your way to victory!
SS_tips_027	Pokémon Camp
SS_tips_028	In your Pokémon Camp, you and your Pokémon can\nplay together and even eat together, growing closer\nthrough the experience! If your Pokémon grow very\nclose to you, they may even try extra hard for you\nduring battle!
SS_tips_029	You can play using your Joy-Con, too! If you slide\nyour Joy-Con off your system, you can wave one\nabout to throw a ball for your Pokémon to retrieve\nor wave a Poké Toy for their delight. If you waggle\nthat Poké Toy, you might even entice Pokémon\nhanging out farther back in your camp to come play!
SS_tips_030	When you set up camp in the Wild Area, you’ll be\nable to play with up to three other Trainers at a time.\nAll kinds of people and Pokémon might stumble upon\nyour camp, even those you’ve never met before,\nso get to know them as you play together!
SS_tips_031	Cooking at Camp
SS_tips_032	Cook up a fine curry while out camping by selecting\ningredients and Berries of your liking!\nYour curries will get more delicious if you choose to\ndo things like using rare ingredients or adding lots\nof Berries, too.
SS_tips_033	Once you start cooking, fan the flames with your fan\nto keep things hot enough, and stir things up with your\nladle to keep ’em moving. Only don’t go overboard—\nyou don’t want to spill! The last step will be to add a\nbit of soul into it at just the right timing, and you’ll\nhave made a masterpiece for your Pokémon to enjoy!
SS_tips_034	After you finish cooking, it’ll be time for everyone to\ndig in together. Eating a tasty curry can have a number\nof effects on the Pokémon that are at your camp,\nincluding restoring their HP and making them feel\nmore friendly toward you!
SS_tips_036	Pokémon Dens
SS_tips_037	The pillars of red light you’ll see in the Wild Area\nmark Pokémon Dens. Dynamax Pokémon dwell in\nthese dens, and you’ll be able to battle them by\ninvestigating the den. You can start the battle on your\nown or get up to three other players to help you out!
SS_tips_040	Max Raid Battles
SS_tips_041	Defeat a Dynamax Pokémon, and you’ll get a chance\nat catching it!\nAdditionally, there are some rare items that you can\nonly obtain by battling Dynamax Pokémon!
SS_tips_042	When wild Pokémon Dynamax, they become\nincredibly powerful. They may unleash multiple moves\nin a row and take other actions you won’t see in a\nregular battle. Working together with other Trainers\nwill be key as you take on these Dynamax Pokémon\ntogether as a team of four.
SS_tips_043	The Flying Taxis
SS_tips_044	If you use the Flying Taxi service, one of their\nwell-trained Corviknight will have you zipping across\nthe Galar region to your desired destination in no\ntime at all! Just open up the X menu, and use the\nTown Map to choose where you want to go!
SS_tips_046	Pokémon Boxes
SS_tips_047	You can keep extra Pokémon in your Pokémon Boxes.\nYou’ve got your own Boxes in the Pokémon storage\nsystem, which you can access at the Rotom Information\nterminals (Rotomi) found in Pokémon Centers\neverywhere. You can retrieve Pokémon from your\nBoxes at any Rotomi you visit, too!
SS_tips_053	Poké Jobs
SS_tips_054	Pokémon are in high demand as helpers in the Galar\nregion, and you’re able to send your own Pokémon\nout to help out on jobs!\nThe Pokémon you send out will grow stronger from\nthe experience they gain!
SS_tips_055	The job postings will be updated every day.\nGood things will begin to happen if you send lots of\nPokémon to many jobs, so keep an eye out for new\npostings and help out as much as you can!
SS_tips_058	The Gym Challenge
SS_tips_059	The Gym Challenge is an event in which aspiring\nTrainers travel around the Galar region to try to\ncollect Gym Badges from eight of its Gyms.\nTo earn a Gym Badge, you have to complete that\nGym’s mission and also defeat its Gym Leader.
SS_tips_060	Live Competitions
SS_tips_061	Live Competitions let you gather together with others\nand have competitions with one another.\nThese can be casual Friendly Competitions, which are\nhosted among friends, or Official Competitions.\nIf you want to find out about current or upcoming\nOfficial Competitions, check out Pokémon’s\nofficial website.
SS_tips_062	Hosting a Competition
SS_tips_063	Live Competitions can be hosted by anyone—\nincluding you!\nSet up the rules you’d like everyone to battle with,\nand then you can share them with all your competition\nparticipants using your system’s communication features!\nFor more information, head to Pokémon’s official website!
SS_tips_064	Casual Battles
SS_tips_065	Please observe the following rules when taking part in\nCasual Battles:\n• Battle Teams must be made up of [VAR FF00(0006)]six different Pokémon[VAR FF00(0000)].\n• No two Pokémon can [VAR FF00(0006)]hold the same item[VAR FF00(0000)].
SS_tips_066	You can take part in Casual Battles even with special\nPokémon in your Battle Team.\nEnjoy battles with all your favorite Pokémon!
SS_tips_067	Ranked Battles
SS_tips_068	Please observe the following rules when taking part in\nRanked Battles:\n• Battle Teams must be made up of [VAR FF00(0006)]six different Pokémon[VAR FF00(0000)].\n• No two Pokémon can [VAR FF00(0006)]hold the same item[VAR FF00(0000)].\n• Teams must not contain[VAR FF00(0006)] any special Pokémon[VAR FF00(0000)].
SS_tips_069	You’ll earn or lose points based on the results of your\nRanked Battles.\nOnce you’ve gained a certain number of points from\nyour Ranked Battles, you’ll go up in rank. On the other\nhand, if you lose enough points, you’ll go down in rank.
SS_tips_070	Ranks are sorted into different tiers. Once you reach\na new tier, you won’t fall back down into a lower tier,\neven if you lose in your Ranked Battles.\nFor example, once you’ve reached the Ultra Ball Tier,\nyou won’t fall back down into the Great Ball Tier,\nregardless of how many battles you lose.
SS_tips_071	Ranked Battles are held during set periods.\nEach of these set periods is called a season.\nOnce one season ends, a new season will begin.\nWhen a new season begins, all players will have their\nranks lowered. At this time only, you might find that\nyou’ve moved down a tier.
SS_tips_072	The players who reach the highest rank in Ranked\nBattles will no longer battle to reach a higher rank, but\ninstead to see where they place among the best.\nA Trainer’s place in the highest rank will go up or down\nbased on the results of their battles.
SS_tips_073	Online Competitions
SS_tips_074	Online Competitions can be broken down into two\ncategories: Official Competitions and\nFriendly Competitions.
SS_tips_075	In Official Competitions, you take part in special\nbattles with a variety of different rules and restrictions\nin order to see where you place.\nDetails about the schedule for these competitions and\nrestrictions on what Pokémon you can use in them are\nannounced on Pokémon’s official website.
SS_tips_076	Friendly Competitions are competitions that are held\nby players themselves. These are casual battles where\nplayers come together to battle one another.\nYou can try your hand at plenty of Friendly Competitions!
SS_tips_077	Search for an Official Competition or a\nFriendly Competition, and enter one to take\npart in battles once the competition begins.\nSearch out competitions with rules that sound like a\nfun challenge or that allow you to take part with the\nPokémon you like!
SS_tips_078	Pokémon Boxes
SS_tips_079	You can use Pokémon Boxes to swap Pokémon in\nyour party for Pokémon you left at a Pokémon\nCenter’s PC.\nTo access the Boxes, select Pokémon from the\nmenu and then press the R Button.
SS_tips_080	Information about Ranked Battles
SS_tips_082	Fishing
SS_tips_083	If you see shadows in the water, you’ll likely find\nPokémon lurking beneath them. Face such a shadow\nand press the A Button to cast your line and try to\nfish up a catch! If your Fishing Rod shakes, press\nthe A Button once more to reel in a Pokémon.\nTry fishing wherever you spot these shadows!
SS_tips_085	Rental Teams
SS_tips_086	Rental Teams allow you to borrow other people’s\nBattle Teams that they’ve shared over the internet,\nor you can share your own team so other players can\nsee how great it is!\nWhen a team is shared, it will be given a team ID.\nInput that team ID when searching for a Rental Team,\nand you’ll be able to borrow the associated Battle Team!
